{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627678"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:50:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:50:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17146"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17146"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0,0.06,0.91,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9836"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77228"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9836"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17146"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62735"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7569"},{"type":"tags","id":"9846"},{"type":"tags","id":"9906"},{"type":"tags","id":"9908"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23034"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23039"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77228","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77228"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EOxygen moves from the alveoli into pulmonary capillaries during normal respiration. This process depends on several physiological factors.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary driving force for oxygen diffusion across the alveolar-capillary membrane?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Osmotic pressure gradient","Facilitated diffusion through channels","Flow due to hydrostatic pressure","Partial pressure gradient","Active transport via membrane proteins"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epartial pressure gradient\u003C/strong\u003E between alveolar gas (PAO2 \u2248 100 mmHg) and pulmonary capillary blood (PvO2 \u2248 40 mmHg) drives oxygen diffusion across the alveolar-capillary membrane. This follows Fick\u0027s law of diffusion, where gases move from areas of high to low partial pressure. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive transport via membrane proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - Oxygen moves by simple diffusion and does not require energy or protein carriers\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlow due to hydrostatic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - Hydrostatic pressure does not drive gas exchange\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitated diffusion through channels\u003C/strong\u003E - Oxygen molecules are small enough to diffuse directly through the phospholipid bilayer\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsmotic pressure gradient\u003C/strong\u003E - Osmotic forces affect fluid movement but not gas diffusion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe rate of oxygen diffusion depends on multiple factors indicated by Fick\u0027s law of diffusion, including the partial pressure gradient, surface area for diffusion, membrane thickness and the diffusion coefficient of oxygen. Other factors like capillary transit time and the rate at which oxygen binds to haemoglobin also influence oxygen diffusion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The alveolar gas equation calculates the alveolar partial pressure of oxygen using atmospheric pressure, water vapour pressure, the fraction of inspired oxygen, the respiratory quotient, and arterial partial pressure of carbon dioxide.","Normal alveolar-arterial oxygen gradient is 5-10 mmHg in young healthy individuals, and increases with age.","Oxygen diffuses from areas of high partial pressure (alveoli) to low partial pressure (pulmonary capillaries) across the alveolar-capillary membrane."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Boron W. F., Boulpaep E. L. Medical Physiology. (3rd edition). US. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62735"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17146"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62735"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T13:37:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T13:37:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9836"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77228"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/